Think of it like a RESTAURANT BILL:
MENU BOARD (Menu Entity)
─────────────────────────
Burger        ₹200
  discount     10%
  final price ₹180   ← what customer sees
  
Pizza         ₹300
  discount     0%
  final price ₹300
CUSTOMER'S BILL (OrderItem Entity)
─────────────────────────────────────
Item        Qty   UnitPrice   Subtotal
─────────────────────────────────────
Burger       2     ₹180        ₹360   ← snapshot of menu price
Pizza        1     ₹300        ₹300
TOTAL BILL (Orders Entity)
──────────────────────────
totalAmount    = ₹660   ← sum of all subtotals
discountAmount = ₹50    ← coupon code applied
taxAmount      = ₹33    ← 5% GST
deliveryCharge = ₹40    ← delivery fee
──────────────────────────
finalAmount    = ₹683   ← what customer pays

Now why each price exists — simply:
Menu prices:
price           = ₹200   → original listed price
discountPercent = 10%    → item level offer (today's special)
discountedPrice = ₹180   → what customer sees on menu
This is just the MENU BOARD — prices of dishes.

OrderItem prices:
unitPrice = ₹180   → SNAPSHOT of menu price at time of order
quantity  = 2
subtotal  = ₹360   → unitPrice × quantity
This is ONE LINE IN THE BILL — e.g. "2 Burgers = ₹360"
Why snapshot? Because:
TODAY:    Burger = ₹180 → customer ordered → saved ₹180
TOMORROW: Admin changes Burger = ₹250

Old order still shows ₹180 ✅
New order shows ₹250 ✅

Orders prices:
totalAmount    = ₹660  → add ALL orderItem subtotals
discountAmount = ₹50   → coupon code discount (order level)
taxAmount      = ₹33   → GST on whole bill
deliveryCharge = ₹40   → delivery fee
finalAmount    = ₹683  → final amount customer pays
This is the COMPLETE BILL — total of everything.
         
         